Triumph of the populist right in Austria, together they make up 29%
The early elections to the Austrian parliament have brought, according to the first approximate results, a considerable weakening of both parties in the current grand coalition and a marked strengthening of the populist right-wing party.
The Austrian People's Party (OVP) has suffered heavy losses, with the position of its current chairman, Wilhelm Molterer, seriously faltering.
On the other hand, the leader of the Alliance for the Future of Austria (BZO), the head of the Carinthian state government, Jörg Haider, is preparing his triumphant return to national politics.
According to the approximate results, the Social Democracy (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, thus losing 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last elections in 2006.
Worse still has ended the OVP that loses 25.6 percent, almost nine percent of the vote.
It is the worst, literally catastrophic, result in the post-war history of these two great Austrian parties and especially for the popular parties who called these early elections.
As early as July, when the OVP left the coalition, the Popular Party had a considerable advantage over the SPO in terms of preference.
It's clear, however, that the voters punished them for letting the government go down.
Already in the first reactions to the results speculations were heard about the resignation of the party president and, until today, vice chancellor, Wilhelm Molterer.
Observers believe that this could be achieved as early as Monday at the extraordinary meeting of the party's leadership.
Such a development would obviously facilitate the way to the constant and more approximate starting point of the election results, i.e. the renewal of the grand coalition between SPO and OVP.
In view of the reinforcement of both parties of the populist right - the Liberals (FPO) have gained about 18 percent and the BZO, eleven percent of the votes - and that the Social Democrats at the same time expressed their fears that the same thing would happen again in 1999 when the Popular negotiated with the Populists (then FPO was a unit, but in 2005 it broke off from BZO) for a coalition government that came to generate a sanction from the European Union.
This is clearly the case for Haider, who has already announced that he is prepared to collaborate with any party and is already returning to Vienna, to national politics.
The Green Party also made it to parliament, although it lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
No other party clearly exceeded the four per cent threshold and is therefore not part of the parliament.
