Turkey expands its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey was a member of the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate the interior of this country.
On the eastern side of the Bosphorus, perhaps only 20 paces inland into Asia, lies one of the most interesting relics of disastrous imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects, Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu, in neo-Renaissance style.
At least, that's what the guides say.
The building is set to face the end of the platforms and carries in front two towers, one for each corner, all resembling a typical German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The building at your complex is a little decadent.
But once the vaulted box office was over, there was no doubt whatever the greatness of the enterprise that this was the most western door.
The station was inaugurated in August 1908 by the German Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a latecomer in the imperial game, had the ambition to dominate the Middle East through this railway that cordoned off Damascus, Baghdad, and beyond into what is now Saudi Arabia.
However, the ambitions of this imperial Germany failed during the First World War.
His railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his Arab irregulars.
Because of the relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, it fell under the influence of the Soviet Union.
British rule and as the forces advanced into Egypt, they pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
The news was bad for Hyderpasha station too.
In 1917, a munitions train exploded, destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources commented that it was sabotage.
Since then, the station has been in decline and has been left out of history.
But today this railway, the gateway to Anatolia and all the eastern centres, serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's willingness to expand its diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party - the AKP - has planned a new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation of the surrounding regions, generated by the frozen borders of the Cold War, has disappeared.
Now there's a new policy of collaboration.
The Turkish Government has excellent relations with Israel and Syria, with both the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and, of course, with the European Union and the United States.
