Suat Kiniklioglu could be a centre-right politician from almost any party in Europe.
Suit, tie, I'm sure he still has a Blackberry.
'The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate neighbourhood.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he says.
Turkey has been cut off in its relations with the interior.
Today you have to look at the same time to the East and the West.
It's not a case if it's not towards one or the other.
You have to do both.
"But surely at some point", I ask, "Turkey might be forced to choose?"
"Turkey", he replies, "does not want to face that choice".
The European Union must not be allowed to continue to be a party to the international community, and the European Union must not be allowed to continue to be a party to the international community.
The message seems to be: with Turkey on board, Europe as a whole can metaphorically set up those rail lines that open up the world to East Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after a second night of sleeplessness, my thoughts turn to the two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Conu, who had assisted in the construction of this building 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to learn that Europe's ambitions in the Middle East would now largely be in the hands of Turkey.
And waiting at the terminal for the ferry that will take me back across the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was considered "the sick man of Europe".
