The 'bee car' that avoids collisions
To advance the development of accident prevention technologies, Nissan has this time been inspired by nature, specifically by bees.
The Japanese company has created a robot that, based on the flight of bees, avoids accidents.
This is the Bio-Mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision avoidance technologies.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co. Advanced Technical Center have developed this little robot in collaboration with the Center for Advanced Science and Technology Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo, Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doi, general director of Public Relations for Technology and Brand Management Research and Development, the BR23C is presented as an extension of Nissan's four-area Safety Shield.
This robot is intended to reinforce the collision-prevention capability of the brand's vehicles.
During their flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space that looks a lot like the Nissan Safety Shield.
But most importantly, the bee's compound eyes, capable of seeing at an angle of more than 300 degrees in all directions, allow it to fly uninterruptedly within its own personal space.
To recreate this visual function, engineers designed what they have called a laser range finder.
It detects obstacles up to two metres away within a radius of 180 degrees ahead of the BR23C, calculates the distance to the object and sends a signal to an onboard microprocessor which immediately results in the collision avoidance.
"Once it detects an obstacle, the little robot will imitate the movements of a bee and immediately change direction by turning its wheels at a right or a left angle to avoid collision.
The biggest difference with any existing system is that the evasive maneuver is entirely instinctive.
If it were not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and the project's lead engineer.
Unlike a bee, the robot cannot swerve up or down, or diagonally; it can only move in two dimensions and in the direction that allows it to turn its wheels and not in infinite directions and ways like bees.
For this reason, Nissan has used a rotation function, in addition to acceleration and deceleration, to avoid collisions with the small robot.
"This device only needs to process information every few seconds, and act on that data.
It requires no storing of information or intuitive logic for previous maneuvers, so it can run continuously with only a couple of dozen KB of memory.
This may surprise you, but we're not talking about gigabytes of memory, or even mega-gigs".
This is the first step in developing new technologies for instant collision avoidance, a technology that Nissan predicts will be introduced in mass production cars within ten years.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than the lithium ion variety.
Another possible future application of this technology could be the integration of the unit with a GPS satellite navigation system to guide the driver to their destination by avoiding obstacles in the way.
