Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
Refound the republic around 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of the Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, the Bolivian Evo Morales and the Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
This Sunday, following the example of his colleagues and friends, is the third day in which a draft for a new Constitution was put to the vote.
Mission accomplished as 64% of voters voted "yes" to the referendum, according to the official results which referred to 80% of the suffrages.
According to these results, the "no" got 28%, 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were blank votes.
For the draft Constitution to be adopted, it had to receive half the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two exit polls and a count by a non-governmental organisation had announced a broad victory for the "yes", estimating between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa had also claimed the victory of his draft Constitution on the night of Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution triumphed in a crushing way", he had assured, congratulating the Ecuadorians who head the government in Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
Rafael Correa has been congratulated by Chávez and Morales but also by his Chilean colleague Micaela Bachelet.
The elections, which will take place in complete calm, according to the observation mission of the Organization of American States (OEA), referred to a text of 444 points that consolidated the "new socialism" defended by the president.
The draft Constitution implies the increase in the power of the State over the economy, reserving for it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially thanks to the extraction of oil by foreign companies and thanks to foreign currencies sent by its emigrants.
Led by Correa, elected in 2006, the bill also grants strengthened powers to the head of state, who can serve up to two consecutive four-year terms each and will have the possibility of dissolving the Assembly.
Correa has already announced that he will use this power and seek a new term in February 2009.
The constitution also consolidates the principle of free health and education services that the president began to establish in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, in which 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also provides for the prohibition of the presence of foreign troops, which will put an end to the agreement between Quito and Washington on the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for American anti-drug operations.
19 kidnapped people have been released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the raid against the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions captured ten days ago.
They're in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian companions who were kidnapped in the desert ten days ago arrived unharmed in the Egyptian capital after being released on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been released by the Egyptian special forces in Chad.
They all looked good when they arrived at 15:30 on board a special plane at the Al Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
Helicopters immediately transported them to the hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical tests, so they have not been able to speak to the press.
"They are in good health" and "no ransom was paid" to the kidnappers, Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garana said at the airport.
On September 19, these hostages fell into the hands of 35 unknown kidnappers while enjoying an off-road safari in a desert area at the foot of Mount Ouanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, and have since been moving from one hole to another.
The group consisted of eleven tourists - five Italians, five Germans and a Romanian - and eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of the Aegyptous travel agency, in charge of the safari's organization.
An Egyptian security official said that 30 members of the special forces, transported on board two helicopters, had launched the assault during the night before dawn.
"An exchange of fire occurred, and half of the kidnappers were killed, the others have fled", said this official who requested anonymity.
According to him, 150 members of the Egyptian special forces unit "Blitz" were sent to Sudan, where they were supported by German and Italian commandos.
The Italian Foreign Minister, Franco Frattini, mentioned in Belgrade the role played by secret agents and members of the Italian special forces.
"We have to admit that we have achieved this result thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of our men in the secret services, the special forces", he said, without going into detail.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The Sudanese army claimed on Tuesday that it intercepted a SUV carrying the kidnappers during a patrol, killing six of them, including the Chadian chief, and arresting two others.
He also claimed that they were linked to a Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Movement-Unity (SLA-U), a claim immediately denied by the group.
Letters - Silent majority of culture
A debate on the financing of culture is making headlines and occupying the current election campaign.
It's better this way.
But one sector of our cultural life is always forgotten.
Who will stand up to denounce the miserable sums that are given to the starving little museums, archives, archaeological digs or national historical sites?
What politician will dare to remind the federal government of its neglect of its monuments and heritage buildings?
Why don't we have real laws that actually preserve our heritage like in Canada and Quebec?
Did you know that the French government is spending three and a half million euros to restore the castle of Chinon in the Loire Valley?
In the United States, it is written in your Constitution that the protection of heritage is part of the culture of the American people and that this heritage has to be protected by all citizens, all elected officials and all government departments, and all this, in concert.
In Quebec, at least 40,000 people, grouped in 211 historical, heritage, archival and genealogical societies, are concerned with researching history, preserving private archives and preserving archaeological sites.
It is these that are often the watchdogs of our heritage, who protest with energy and desperation when promoters and managers launch their bulldozers against our old stones and our forgotten cemeteries.
For when, a monument to history and heritage?
The Dutch governments nationalise part of Fortis Bank.
The Dutch States - the first in Europe - will help with a nationalisation of the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis which is in trouble due to the impact of the mortgage crisis on the North American market: the three countries will support this financial and insurance institution which also has business in Hungary with a total of EUR 11.2 billion.
This weekend the governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands held high-level consultations with the President of the European Central Bank and the Commissioner responsible for economic competition.
Fortis Bank was the first to suffer from the euro area crisis in the context of the international financial crisis that has been occurring in several waves for more than a year, so the decisions taken with regard to the Bank can in a sense be considered as precedents.
According to the decision adopted in the early hours of Sunday, the three States will buy approximately half (49 percent) of the property owned by the Bank in their area.
The Bank will certainly sell some of its business, including the mainly insurance business it bought last year from the Dutch bank ABN AMRO.
The shares of Fortis started a sharp decline last week and by the second half of the week there were already significant signs of crisis in the institution.
However, analysts agree that with its 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to allow itself to fail.
The company's stock just on Friday fell 12 percent, the lowest point in the last 14 years.
Since January, the value of the stock has dropped by more than two-thirds.
Looking at the current share prices, the total value of the group's capital on the market is around 14 billion euros, but according to the company's executives this is not real.
The Bank's management blamed the sharp fall in Fortis' shares on the uncertainties of the North American market in connection with the approval of the US $700 billion package plan.
On Monday the shares showed a slight increase.
On Friday they appointed Filip Dierckx as the new CEO of the bank.
The Bank also sought private investors, but no firm offer has been made so far.
The Belgian government had previously assured investors that they had nothing to worry about, they would not lose their money.
There was no panic among the bank's customers so far, they did not raid the bank offices to withdraw their money.
Fortis has its own branch in Hungary and has also bought leasing companies.
Fox in the henhouse
In the United States, life and health insurance companies, upon seeing the data on the purchase of medication, often refuse to sign an insurance contract.
Privacy policy experts fear that the market for personal data will become uncontrollable.
"There are programmes for the protection of personal data, which in all cases link the use of prescription data to the approval of the person concerned.
It must be in independent hands, otherwise "we leave the henhouse to the fox" - the Washington Post quotes Richard Dick, designer of the prescription tracking program.
Insurance companies make the price of insurance and the amount of compensation depend on the client's health condition and if they believe that the risk is excessive, they simply do not make the contract.
They sent the client to a doctor's office and signed the contract with him knowing the result of the examination.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: with the customer identification number he easily obtains from pharmacies the list of medicines bought in the last year and a half and the program itself draws the conclusion about the diseases and health status of the customer.
For example, if you consistently take large doses of cholesterol-lowering pills, it indicates that your blood fat level is practically incurably high, and you are immediately put in a higher risk category.
There are many versions of the scheme, some even setting a risk number, so the insurance company and the administration have little to do, although there are some minor difficulties in this respect.
Among the disadvantages of the programme are that some medicines are multi-purpose, for example certain substances are used both for headache and for heat waves and even as antidepressants.
The latter is a major risk-increasing factor for insurance companies whereas the former is not.
Special companies were set up to consult and process this data, which, before acquiring the necessary information from pharmacies, ask for the patient's approval.
The authorities are already forcing them to do this, although they have not received a fine for their negligence so far.
Some companies are also developing lab test results and linking them to drug consumption data to obtain more accurate information about the patient's health status.
More and more companies have access to this data and simultaneously it is becoming more and more difficult to control its use.
There is a specific law for the protection of personal health data, but it applies only to insurance companies and healthcare providers.
A bill is already before Congress that gives the authority the right to control companies specialized in the provision of personal data.
Dick Richard recognises that this is insufficient: he has therefore developed his programme, which will require the specific approval of the individual for the provision of his own personal data.
It is another matter that such a person cannot deny his approval, because otherwise the insurance companies will not sign the contract with him.
So the hens, after all, are exposed to the fox's goodwill.
