EU to double trade with India
As the European Union and India are each other's trading partners, this issue along with other largely global issues dominated the agenda of the ninth summit.
A French-Indian summit will also be held today, mainly to discuss cooperation in nuclear energy.
Although the European Union recognises that India is a developing great democratic power that should have more say and vote in international affairs but member countries have not yet been able to come to a common denominator on whether they should support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
This question was not raised at the ninth summit which began yesterday in Marseilles.
The French President Nicolas Sarkozy, the EU's acting president, the Commission President José Manuel Barroso and Javier Solana, the EU's chief foreign policy representative, welcomed Manmohan Singh, the prime minister of India, with whom they reached an agreement to double their trade in five years, to over 100 billion euros.
Given that trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not an overly ambitious target.
The 26 existing bilateral civil aviation agreements with India have been legally harmonized, so that air transport will also be able to fly in the future.
India wants to sign the free trade agreement with the Union by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the negotiations.
The goal is balance, because while the EU is India's top trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among the Union's trading partners.
The summit turned its attention to global affairs.
The two sides condemned the Afghan and Pakistani situation and terrorism in all its forms and called for a UN conference.
The conclusion of the Doha round of trade liberalization was also pressed for, although both sides bear a great deal of responsibility for its failure.
The EU has confirmed that it will stick to its energy and climate programme, that is, until 2020 it wants to reduce polluting emissions by at least 20 per cent.
India also agrees with this, as well as the climate conference next year should reach a global agreement and reduce by 2050 by fifty percent the production of gases that produce greenhouse effect.
They also wanted to prevent food prices from rising and supported the convening of an international conference to review the financial crisis.
The Indian Prime Minister is travelling to the French capital today, where he will sign an agreement on the peaceful use of nuclear energy at a bilateral meeting.
Paris was confident that French companies would receive orders worth 20 billion euros to build nuclear reactors.
According to news agency reports the agreement would be for a period of 15 years.
In Frankfurt, more than 300 Italian publishers
Strong presence of Italian publishers at the Frankfurt International Book Fair.
More than 300 Italian publishers will be attending the 60th edition of the Buchmesse, the most important international trade fair for rights.
The Frankfurt International Book Fair is expecting more than 7 000 exhibitors from 102 countries to occupy the 171790 square metres of the show, with more than 403 000 titles on display and with Turkey as the guest of honour.
The Italian government will be represented at the opening ceremony by the Undersecretary of the Ministry for Cultural Heritage and Activities, Francisco Maria Giro. Italy will be institutionally and effectively present with a 264 square metre exhibition space.
A meeting with the press will follow in the Room Struktur in Hall 5.0 of the Buchmesse: this will be the occasion to present numbers, trends and prospects on the state of publishing houses in Italy.
The weight of books by foreign authors on total Italian production, and in particular on books for adults and adolescents, is gradually decreasing.
We found the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago.
The wreckage of the plane belonging to Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3rd, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, there were no human remains.
Madera County Commissioner John Anderson has put to rest the remaining doubts: "The plane has been located, we have sent a squad, and now we have confirmation that it is the very one that Steve Fossett was flying over the day of his disappearance" said in a press conference.
The Commissioner has stated that no human remains have been found on the plane or in the surroundings.
The 63-year-old millionaire was declared dead in February.
The American office for transportation safety (MTSB) has informed that a few hours after the sighting of the wreckage, a squad of investigators has been sent who has identified the device: it is the Bellanca 8kcab, dispersed since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington in Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal remains were found by a couple near his Mammoth Lakes home.
It's two documents in Fossett's name, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweatshirt.
The search for Fossett had been discontinued a month after his disappearance.
The millionaire had earned himself a place in history by a long series of firsts.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he had become the first man to complete a solo two-week flight around the world in a hot air balloon.
Three years later, I had flown around the world nonstop.
Among his records, also that for having flown at 15,445 meters high, over the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
